ame="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets><DescTPC fid="de"><DescField fid="ipc">ABINS.YY HNAG.YY M/FCL N/CMY N/CRM N/GEN N/LWS R/ASI R/CH R/FEO WANDA.YY </DescField><DescField fid="ipd">WSJ WSJ.com WSJ.com Site Search WSJAsia WSJEurope WSJ Japanese Online WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com WSJSunday ANBANG ACQUISITIONS CHINA BUSINESS CORRUPTION CORRUPTION IN CHINA FORMER ANBANG CHAIRMAN TRIAL WU XIAOHUI TRIAL SB127189489785985032805045841293717320515301 Xiaohui, Xiaohui PRO SYND WSJ-PRO-NP CODES_REVIEWED China News </DescField><DescField fid="ipcns">OCHN </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">World</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Former Anbang Chairman Expresses Remorse at Fraud Trial; Charges against Wu Xiaohui include forging documents, raising over $10 billion using fraudulent means and abusing power to appropriate company funds</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>SHANGHAIâ€”Wu Xiaohui, who built a small insurer into China's third-largest and a global dealmaker, asked for leniency in court to charges he falsified financial reports to exaggerate business assets and mask benefits to himself.</Para><Para>At the conclusion to his one-day trial, Mr. Wu expressed remorse and indicated he understood the charges against him relating to his former position as chairman of Anbang Insurance Group Co., according to a summary published by the Shanghai No. 1 Intermediate People's Court.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>The court didn't specify whether Mr. Wu entered a plea to the charges, which included forging documents, raising over $10 billion using fraudulent means and abusing power to appropriate company funds and hide his control of Anbang. Mr. Wu's lawyers didn't respond to requests for comment.</Para><Para>The charges are considered severe and follow a government <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-s-insurance-regulator-to-take-over-anbang-insurance-owner-of-the-waldorf-astoria-1519351766?mod=searchresults&amp;page=2&amp;pos=12">takeover last month of Anbang</ELink> after regulators found that unspecified illegal registration filings by the insurer could "seriously threaten the solvency of the company." In China, the government intervention was interpreted as evidence authorities consider the firm with $300 billion in assets too big too fail, after just 14 years of operation.</Para><Para>Prosecutors told the court the takeover kept Mr. Wu's actions from harming policyholders.</Para><Para>Anbang's reorganization and Mr. Wu's trial are part of a government offensive against brash private firms, some of which seemed to operate at times with official support. Tycoons have disappeared into investigations or been forced to backpedal on acquisitions and other strategies that turned companies like Anbang, Dalian Wanda Group and HNA Group Co. into high-profile institutions in international deal-making.</Para><Para>Known by colleagues as a stickler for financial details, Mr. Wu orchestrated deals for Anbang to scoop up insurers in the Netherlands and South Korea, a bank in Belgium and property in the U.S. After his <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/waldorf-astoria-hotel-sale-completed-1423705536">$1.95 billion purchase of the Waldorf Astoria</ELink> in New York, the most expensive for a U.S. hotel at the time, Mr. Wu reasoned "this trophy hotel is very cheap in my eyes."</Para><Para>As policy makers grew concerned over the flood of money leaving China and slammed on the brakes, Chinese outbound investments fell around two-thirds last year, according to research firm Mergermarket. Official pushback has persisted; authorities recently launched an investigation into the founder of China's largest private oil company, CEFC China Energy Co., amid pending agreements to buy into a Russian oil producer, a Czech financial firm and an insurer in Portugal.</Para><Para>Prosecution of Mr. Wu has been notably swift.</Para><Para>In the first photos of Mr. Wu seen since he was detained last June, he appeared in a small courtroom before three judges wearing a blue suit and flanked by two policeman. He told the court he was a shareholder in Anbang but disputed characterizations of his outright control of the firm or that its expansion was unusual, according to the court's summaries, which were posted to its official microblog account.</Para><Para>In a press statement, Anbang said the case related to Mr. Wu's personal matters because he was no longer chairman. It said the firm's business operations are stable and generate "sufficient cash flow to fulfill its policy commitments to all Anbang customers."</Para><Para>The court described Mr. Wu as the primary shareholder in Anbang at its formation in 2004 and said he maintained nearly full control of the insurer through dozens of shareholding companies, even as it significantly expanded the capital base. For instance, the court said he controlled 37 companies holding over 98% of Anbang at the end of 2014, noting that it virtually doubled its registered capital in just nine months that year to 61.9 billion yuan.</Para><Para>Prosecutors alleged Mr. Wu bulked up Anbang on insurance products that he got rights to sell using forged financial reports. When fundraising exceeded regulatory limits by hundreds of billions of yuan, prosecutors alleged, Mr. Wu ignored them. He "took advantage of his positions, illegally taking possession of the companies' funds, appropriating the funds," prosecutors alleged. "The amounts were especially large."</Para><Para>According to the court, one regulator testified that Mr. Wu conducted "huge fake capital injections" and transferred company assets into companies under his personal control, providing false information to regulators and the public.</Para><Para>Mr. Wu remains in custody. Guilt is virtually assured in Chinese criminal cases, though the court didn't announce a date the verdict will be handed down.â€‹</Para><Para>Yang Bailin, a Shanghai-based attorney with the King &amp; Capital Law Firm who isn't involved in the case, described the charge of fraudulent fund-raising as particularly serious because it ascribes malicious intent to the perpetrator. Another charge, "duty-related appropriation," is used against employees of private companies and is akin to accusations of official corruption, Mr. Yang said.</Para><Para>Anbang's travails came amid a broader regulatory crackdown on an insurance industry that expanded rapidly in part by selling high-yielding products officials said enriched tycoons at the expense of â€‹the â€‹publicâ€‹ and raised risks of trouble for the broader financial system.</Para><Para>Over the past year or so, the chief insurance regulator was cashiered for corruption, a billionaire property tycoon was banned from the insurance industry for 10 years after regulators found an insurer he controlled made fake reports, and another developer-turned-insurer was hit with administrative penalties over its investment practices.</Para><Para>Bankers are now on the lookout for possible asset sales by Anbang; a spokesman for the firm said Wednesday it hasn't sold assets.</Para><Para>Anbang's treatment has been harsher than what has been faced by other firms. "The takeover of Anbang exemplifies China's increasing heavy-handedness in containing financial system risks," debt ratings firm Standard &amp; Poor's said this week. "We see this move as closing the chapter on aggressive expansion by Chinese insurance conglomerates."</Para><Para>Liyan Qi in Beijing and Chunying Zhang in Shanghai contributed to this article.</Para><Para>Write to James T. Areddy at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:james.areddy@wsj.com">james.areddy@wsj.com</ELink></Para></TailParas>